In Kubernetes (and Amazon EKS), draining and cordoning are used for managing workloads during node maintenance or upgrades.

Some popular use cases can be:
A. Node Maintenance: Update or patch the underlying EC2 instance.
B. Node Replacement: Migrate workloads to a new node.
C. Cluster Scaling: Decommission nodes during downscaling.

# Cordoning a Node
1. Cordoning a node marks it as unschedulable, preventing new pods from being assigned to the node. Existing pods continue to run.

Command to Cordon a Node:
kubectl cordon <node-name>
Example:

kubectl cordon ip-192-168-0-123.ec2.internal
Output might look like: node/ip-192–168–0–123.ec2.internal cordoned

Effect:
New pods are not scheduled on the node.
Existing pods remain unaffected.

2. Draining an EKS Node
Draining a node evicts all non-daemonset pods from it, ensuring the workloads are safely migrated to other nodes before maintenance.

Command to Drain a Node:
kubectl drain <node-name> --ignore-daemonsets --delete-emptydir-data
Flags:

--ignore-daemonsets: DaemonSet-managed pods are not evicted.
--delete-emptydir-data: Deletes pods with emptyDir volumes (temporary storage).
Exmaple:

kubectl drain ip-192-168-0-123.ec2.internal --ignore-daemonsets --delete-emptydir-data
Output might look something like node/ip-192–168–0–123.ec2.internal drained

Effect:
Evicts all non-daemonset pods.
Marks the node as unschedulable.
DaemonSet pods remain running on the node.

** Error Handling **
Some Popular Error handling scenarios and possible solutions :

Error 1: Pod Stuck During Draining:

Use --force and --grace-period=0 to forcibly evict pods:
kubectl drain <node-name> --ignore-daemonsets --delete-emptydir-data --force --grace-period=0

Error 2: DaemonSet Pods on the Node:

DaemonSet pods are ignored by default with --ignore-daemonsets.

Error3: Unschedulable Pods:

Ensure the cluster has sufficient resources to reschedule evicted pods.

**** Common kubectl commands ****
# Step 1: List all nodes to identify the node for maintenance
kubectl get nodes

# Step 2: Cordon the node to prevent new pods from being scheduled
NODE_NAME="ip-192-168-0-123.ec2.internal"  # Replace with your node name
kubectl cordon $NODE_NAME
echo "Node $NODE_NAME cordoned."

# Step 3: Verify the node is cordoned
kubectl get nodes | grep $NODE_NAME

# Step 4: Drain the node to evict all non-daemonset pods
kubectl drain $NODE_NAME --ignore-daemonsets --delete-emptydir-data
echo "Node $NODE_NAME drained."

# Step 5: Verify all pods are evicted from the node
kubectl get pods --all-namespaces --field-selector spec.nodeName=$NODE_NAME

# Optional: Describe the node to confirm taints and unschedulable status
kubectl describe node $NODE_NAME

# Step 6: Perform maintenance on the node (manual step)

# Step 7: Uncordon the node after maintenance to allow scheduling
kubectl uncordon $NODE_NAME
echo "Node $NODE_NAME uncordoned."

# Step 8: Watch the node and pod status for confirmation
kubectl get nodes -w  # Watch for node status
kubectl get pods --all-namespaces -o wide | grep $NODE_NAME  # Monitor pod reschedu

**** What is a DaemonSet? ****

In Kubernetes, a DaemonSet is a controller that:

- Automatically deploys a Pod on all worker nodes
- Ensures new nodes also get that Pod
- Removes the Pod if the node is removed
- Why DaemonSet is Used

DaemonSets are used for services that must run on:

Every node (or a group of nodes), These are usually:

Monitoring agents
Log collectors
Networking components
Storage agents
Security agents

Common Real-World Examples
Use Case	Example
Log collection	Fluentd, Filebeat
Monitoring	Node Exporter, Datadog Agent
Networking	Calico, Flannel, Cilium
Storage	Ceph agents
Security	Falco
Kubernetes system services	kube-proxy

*** Example ***

Suppose you have 5 worker nodes. If you create a DaemonSet:

Kubernetes runs:
1 Pod on node1
1 Pod on node2
1 Pod on node3
1 Pod on node4
1 Pod on node5

If a new node joins: Pod is automatically created there too.

*** Why Normal Deployment is Not Enough ***

A Deployment may place Pods randomly.
Example:

3 Pods → all may run on same node

But some services need:

1 Pod per node, That is why DaemonSet exists.

Example YAML
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: DaemonSet
metadata:
  name: fluentd
spec:
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: fluentd
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: fluentd
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: fluentd
        image: fluent/fluentd

- How to View DaemonSets ?
# kubectl get daemonsets -A

or

kubectl get ds -A
How DaemonSet Pods Look
kubectl get pods -o wide

You will notice:

Same Pod running on many nodes

Example:

fluentd-abc12   Running   worker1
fluentd-def34   Running   worker2
fluentd-ghi56   Running   worker3

# Why Drain Ignores DaemonSet Pods

When you run:

kubectl drain node1

Kubernetes refuses to delete DaemonSet Pods because:

They are system-level Pods
They are expected to exist on every node
Controller recreates them automatically

So usually we use:

kubectl drain node1 --ignore-daemonsets

This tells Kubernetes:

“Ignore system DaemonSet Pods while draining.”

Real Example

Suppose node has:

Pod	              Type
nginx-app	        Deployment
mysql	            StatefulSet
calico-node	      DaemonSet
kube-proxy	      DaemonSet

In many clusters you will see:

kube-proxy
calico-node
flannel
cilium
node-exporter

These are usually DaemonSets.

Quick Summary

DaemonSet means:

“Run this Pod on every node automatically.”

Used mainly for:

Monitoring
Logging
Networking
Storage
Security agents

*** What will happen to DeamonSet pods after draining ***.
DaemonSet Pods do not stop node maintenance. Kubernetes handles them differently from normal application Pods.

What Happens During Drain

When you run:

kubectl drain worker-node1 --ignore-daemonsets

Kubernetes does:

- Cordon the node
- No new Pods scheduled
- Evict normal Pods, Deployments, StatefulSets, ReplicaSets, etc.
- Ignore DaemonSet Pods, They remain running on the node,

*** Why DaemonSet Pods Are Ignored **

Because they are:

Node-specific system services
Expected to run on every node
Automatically recreated by DaemonSet controller

*** During Reboot or Shutdown ***

Suppose you reboot the node after drain. What happens?

Before reboot

Application Pods already moved to other nodes.

DaemonSet Pods still exist on the node.

Node goes down

All Pods on that node stop:

Normal Pods already evacuated
DaemonSet Pods also stop because node is OFF

Cluster marks node:

NotReady
After Node Comes Back

When node boots again:

Kubelet starts
Node reconnects to cluster
DaemonSet controller checks node
Required DaemonSet Pods start automatically again

*** Can i use deamonsets for normal application pod ***

Yes, Kubernetes technically allows you to run normal applications using a DaemonSet, but in most cases it is not the correct choice.

Use a DaemonSet only when the application must run on every node (or specific nodes).
